The democratic routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is support for private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These are the findings of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts stand out in this year's survey from September and October.
Firstly, the good mood in Latin America
and second, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In numerous countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown rapidly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where the economy has been growing at about 6% annually since 2002, pro-democracy numbers rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since last year's sharp slump.
Yet only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, lowering the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practices. That is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined democratic efforts.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America only experienced a short recession phase and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were cushioned by a stronger social safety net.
(The poverty rate in Latin America rose only modestly in 2009, and has fallen 32% this year, according to reports this week from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America.)
But there are strong differences in sentiment from country to country (see Diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread progressive mentality.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has increased.
For only the second time since the survey began, many Latin American respondents see crime as a bigger problem in their country than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say either they or a family member have been a victim of a crime in the past year. However, levels have fallen from 38% last year, to their lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: approx. 71% of those surveyed nationwide stated that the private economy is indispensable for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Diagram 6).
About 58% said only the market economy can bring their country progress, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of private enterprise), despite the fact that their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is nationalizing many private companies.
Brazil has the greatest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela assuming this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An election defeat
No one expected the November 28 elections in Haiti to be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of poll workers who rushed to help the troubled country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot papers in the gutter, vandalized polling stations and intimidation were just part of the problem.
Polling stations opened hours late.
Many Haitians, many of whom were displaced by January's earthquake, roamed the countryside looking for a choice.
Some eventually gave up altogether.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected frontrunners, have called for the election results to be overturned over alleged fraud.
Protests, some of them violent, broke out across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as "quite good in many respects".
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, serious as they are, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which is said to be indebted to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his nominee, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected runoff election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidation action.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support from the electorate, is declared the winner of the runoff by the electoral authorities, problems could arise.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims are still living in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election had not yet been distributed.
The stakes are high.
Donor countries see legitimate, recognized government as an important step in Haiti's reconstruction.
The Haitians themselves agree.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following her husband's sudden death, Argentina's President, Cristina Fernández, experienced a surge of sympathy that boosted her popularity rating by 20 points to over 50%. This is the highest since she was elected in 2007.
However, whether this will get her re-elected next year depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who continued to steer economic policy even after his wife was elected, often drew up budgets that did not take full account of tax revenue, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenue as they saw fit.
On paper, the Fernández administration lost a majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided, and Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27 led to further rifts.
Some critics of the regime from the ranks of the ruling Peronists backed Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (with one MP slapping another in the face and others accusing the government of bribery), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
"I will not discuss it," said the President.
The 2010 budget now carries over into next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend as she sees fit.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and union wage claims - push the figure to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was rocked by economic crises, said his main goals were growth and poverty reduction, not lowering inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, bullied the private sector and purged the National Institute for Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently whitewashed official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
She has called on the private sector and union leaders to hold talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be capped at 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth spurt with a major devaluation in 2002.
Possibly for this reason Cristina Fernández would like to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government struck a deal with security holders who had opposed the country's earlier debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández appears to be pushing for a deal with Paris Club lenders to whom she owes approximately $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always refused an IMF review, as is customary elsewhere.
But last month Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund would provide "technical assistance" in compiling a new national consumer price index. It looks like this is the first step in cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after the end of her term without the support of her husband.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, most of whom are fed up with Kirchnerism.
By the time the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy she received will have ebbed.
If she wants to win another election, she must choose between quietly overturning many of her husband's political decisions.
Weak applause for China
Taiwan's voters are slowly moving towards closer ties with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the straits?
On November 27, more than 7.5 million voters, or 70% of all eligible voters, turned out to elect mayors and councilors in the five boroughs. This is taken as a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Having developed pioneering business relationships, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma has become a symbol of mainland relations himself. His policies changed relations with mainland China for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but just barely.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) provided three of the five mayors, it did not get a majority of votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which advocates greater independence for Taiwan, received almost 50% of the vote, while the KMT received 45%.
In a presidential election, this would have meant problems for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party's share of the vote has fallen by around 8%.
For the first time, the DPP even entered the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election, the usual incidents in Taiwan such as truck convoys with rioters, flag-waving mass processions and scantily clad dancers took place.
There was even the obligatory mysterious attempted murder.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech on the eve of the election for a KMT candidate,
when a man in the crowd shot him in the face. Lien was wounded and a bystander killed.
Bizarrely, it's not clear if the shooter was trying to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Regardless, according to Tsai Ing-wen, leader of the DPP, the attack marred the election and cast the DPP in a bad light, giving the KMT more votes.
China may have been the campaign's biggest winner.
Remarkably, relations with the mainland were not discussed.
Instead, the candidates debated public housing plans and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their virtual independence and reject China's military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to prioritize its relations with the Beijing government.
This time, however, the DPP also avoided stoking anti-Chinese sentiment too much.
She was reacting to the new awareness that Taiwan's economy cannot survive without China.
For his part, Ma wants confirmation that the majority of Taiwanese support his China policy.
The Beijing government will continue to pursue its strategy of luring Taiwan back into the community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
Certainly, it also wants political integration. But first things first.
It prefers to wait until after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has now reinvented itself.
Two years ago, it was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was in prison for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he vehemently advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai's reign, a new generation of moderate politicians has emerged and the DPP is fighting for the votes of professionals and youth.
Tsai was well received as the DPP's presidential candidate, as was Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything it can to show that it, too, is capable of building close ties with Beijing.
Tsai is planning a think tank as a point of contact between the DPP and China. However, this requires unprejudiced discussions.
Tsai publicly stated that her party offers a "trustworthy alternative" to Ma's hasty rapprochement with China.
Chen seems very upset about this move.
From his cell, he said the DPP candidates would have done better to insist on Taiwan's independence.
He even asked the pragmatist Su to give up the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen's interference, the DPP is struggling to choose its possible candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Ma's scores are poor despite rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
According to a KMT spokesman, he will reorganize his cabinet and local institutions.
The strong position of the DPP suggests that Taiwan's support for a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese view economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "there is already no turning back".
Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding was surprisingly awarded in the Newcomer of the Year category
If you perform at the request of a president, people will take notice.
President Obama himself asked Esperanza Spalding to perform at the 2009 Nobel Prize ceremony. Surprisingly, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer has now been nominated for this year's Grammy in the Newcomer of the Year category.
Given that Spalding has already been a celebrated star on the jazz scene since her 2008 album Esperanza, the nomination seems a bit unusual. But it conforms to Grammy rules, according to which an artist can only have released a maximum of three albums before the release of the album that made them known to the general public.
Her ambitious 2010 album Chamber Music Society is certainly a step forward. And with her lilting voice and keen flair for pop, funk and Latin music, Spalding can easily be compared to Norah Jones 2003, whose huge success in 2003 as a jazz performer in this category comes closest to Spalding's nomination.
The album "Historicity" by the Vijay Iyer Trio was also nominated in the instrumental albums category. This made this critics' darling a smash hit.
Iyer's competitors include veteran saxophonist James Moody's "Moody 4B" and keyboardist John Beasley's "Positootly".
Trombone Shorty, a tough New Orleans favorite and frequent guest on HBO's "Treme," was recognized in the contemporary jazz category, which tends to feature albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLoughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Wild steampunk musician Darcy James Argue's Secret Societ received well-deserved attention in the Large Group category. He goes up against the Billy Childs ensemble with his chamber jazz and the adventurous Dave Holland and his octet, whose life album "Pathways" is a good example of a bassist as a democratic bandleader.
Grammy Nominations: Michael Daugherty, Steve Mackey lead in Classic categories
The classical music nominations for the 53rd Grammy Awards contain a colorful mix of musicians and composers from all over the world.
Topping the list are Michael Daugherty's "Deux Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra in five voices, and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse", an eclectic orchestral work in three voices.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt's Symphony No. 4 "Los Angeles". This piece was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
L.A.-based composer Avner Dorman was also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
Classical nominations are divided into 13 categories ranging from orchestra, opera, choir to solo recordings.
Five artists were nominated in the Classical Producers category this year - Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Among the nominated classical albums are Bruckner's Symphonies Nos. 3 and 4 by the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" performed by the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" by the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" performed by various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Choir.
In the opera category, Berg's "Lulu" by the Royal Opera House Orchestra; Adolf Hasse's "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho's "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin's "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the Mariinsky Theater Orchestra and Chorus; and Arthur Sullivan's "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
As composers, Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" were nominated for a Grammy.
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 was premiered and recorded on January 4th at Disney Hall by the LA Philharmonic conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The approximately 30-minute piece is entitled "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, who is in prison in Russia.
Dorman's "Mondolin Concerto" received a nomination in the Instrumental Solo with Orchestra category.
The LA composer said he wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin artist Avi Avital, who performed the concerto with New York's Metropolis Ensemble.
"I used sounds from the Middle East and a lot of North African tones and rhythms," Dorman explained in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the Orchestral Performance category for a recording of Stravinsky's works with the Chicago Symphony Orchestra under his direction.
The pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin, the organist Paul Jacobs, the violinist Julia Fischer and the harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson were nominated as instrumental soloists.
Only women were nominated as vocal soloists this year, including Anne Sofie von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivicagenaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
Soprano Jessye Norman was nominated in the Classical Crossover category for her recording "Roots - My Life, My Song".
Mosque in Temecula wins planning committee approval
The construction of a mosque in Temecula received unanimous approval from the local planning committee after a five-hour, often heated public hearing.
Critics accused the project of promoting both terrorism and traffic congestion.
However, according to a statement by the commission on Wednesday evening, the new religious center complies with local regulations and will be an aesthetic eye-catcher.
"The project has the support of many good people - Christians, Jews, Baha'is, and many others," said Hadi Nael, chairman of the Temecula Valley Islamic Center Thursday morning.
"As an American, that makes me proud."
"It shows that justice prevails."
"There are few opponents," he added.
"You're just very loud."
"Wonderful people live in this valley."
The session began at 6:00 p.m. and discussions for and against building the center lasted almost until midnight, with votes fairly evenly split on both sides, according to Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper's website.
"There is no more America," read one comment.
"It's another planet of the apes and the Statue of Liberty lies dead in the sand."
"America is finished."
Planned Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including near Ground Zero, the scene of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks on New York City.
In the Temecula Valley, Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has called for non-violence.
His community of approximately 135 families has lived peacefully in Riverside County for years. But they wished for a bigger and better place than the warehouse they rented with a water filtration equipment manufacturer.
The new, approximately 2,300 m2 Mediterranean-style mosque will have two minarets and be around 13 m high.
It is to be built on the approximately 17,500 m2 site on Nicolas Road near Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal the project to the city council.
Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously thought essential to life.
"This organism has two options."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"That makes it very special, even though it's almost kind of an 'alien' life form," explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in Thursday's online edition of Science magazine.
So far, six main elements have been considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, as the scientists found out, the bacterium in Mono Lake, California, continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible," said report co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study looks at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference that did not provide details of the discovery sparked widespread speculation on the internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes, and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
'This work is first because it shows that one element can be substituted for another in fundamental biochemical processes and structures,' added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she hypothesized that exposure to both microbes might be able to substitute one element for the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically in a similar way to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so big that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it basically smears everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, its ability to survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life-form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
According to Jamie S. Foster, associate professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that arsenic can be substituted for phosphorus is not new. But so far there hasn't been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so scientists have assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early geological era," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
Remaining stolen show dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four show dogs stolen from outside a Bellflower motel have been found, the Los Angeles County Sheriff said Thursday.
The four show dogs -- two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis -- disappeared Tuesday when strangers stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van in which the animals were being housed outside a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were spotted Wednesday afternoon, and the final two were spotted Wednesday night, said Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is the dogs are doing well," said Whitmore.
"They are in good condition."
"They have been returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not provide specific information about the location of the dogs or the circumstances that led to their discovery.
"The investigation is still ongoing."
"We don't want to say more about that," explains Whitmore.
"We're following some leads."
The dog's owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available for information Thursday.
They received their two dogs at a county animal shelter in Downey on Wednesday afternoon.
Sheriff's officials found the van and the two dogs in separate locations in Compton.
The Akitas -- Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female -- were unharmed, officials said.
But the corgis Bunny and Peter, who wanted to present Rickard and Peek at the competition this week on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained missing until Wednesday evening.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in town this weekend for the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach, where Trace was scheduled to compete.
As Peek told the Times Wednesday, the other dogs were scheduled to compete in other competitions in the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show.
Southern California is a stop on the couple's nearly month-long tour from dog show to dog show.
On Monday evening, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van in front of their room window.
They took three other dogs -- a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier, and a Brittany -- to their motel room.
The thick-skinned Akitas and Corgis stayed in the van because it was cooler there.
They left the window ajar so the dogs could get some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported their car stolen at 6:00 a.m. Tuesday.
Peek promised a finder's fee to anyone who could provide information about the corgis. The animals were implanted with microchips for identification.
On Thursday it was not yet clear whether a finder's fee would be paid.
The lion roars again after court approval of MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially approved the "prepared" lender plan to pay down $5 billion in debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to launch new movies and TV shows.
According to statements made Thursday, the plan complies with US bankruptcy law requirements, leaving nothing standing in the way of MGM's restart under the direction of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, founders of Spyglass Entertainment. Barber and Birnbaum will lead the somewhat slimmed-down studio as general managers.
The number of employees is reduced from over 400 to around 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 does not actually come into effect until JPMorgan Chase completes a proposed $500 million bond issue to fund new MGM productions.
The company is currently managed by a consortium of the investment bank, which itself has brought in $75 million. Funding is expected to be in place by mid-December.
The studio's restructuring began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co was hired to help management, which was struggling with $300m/year in interest payments, solve its financial woes.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and restructuring expert best known for his work at Krispy Kreme Donuts.
Moelis & Cooper's efforts to resolve MGM's financial woes and pay off the studio's more than 140 creditors took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided in late 2009 to put the company up for sale.
But the auction attracted few bidders and none were willing to pay the $2 billion demanded by creditors.
It all started all over again in the spring of this year when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which, after months of debate and internal disputes, was finally signed by the creditors at the end of October.
If MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multimillion-dollar bonus for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., who have already received $1.2 million, is $9.5 million.
Cooper, who were paid $375,000 a month to run the company, will receive a $4 million "success bonus."
Barber and Birnbaum plan to restart production at MGM. The studio released just one film this year and has a yearly plan of seven or eight films due for release in early 2012.
They are also planning two films after "The Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio requires a separate bond of between $265 million and $275 million for its financial interest in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who funded approximately 18% of the MGM loan, attempted a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the last negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any result.
Tech Toys keeps your gift budget in balance
This year's favorite gift is the iPad, possibly followed by a Microsoft Kinect video console. Both of these gimmicks can make a significant dent in your gift budget.
An iPad costs as much as five BMX bikes for $99, while a Kinect game costs about 10 classic jump ropes or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But you can go easy on your gift budget.
I recently visited three national toy retailers - a Wal-Mart, a Toys "R" Us, and a BJ's Wholesale Club, in search of three electronic toys under $80.
It was immediately clear to me that Moore's Law was in effect. This year the technology toys are more powerful and at the same time cost a little less than last year.
And while fewer new toys are appearing with their own websites, the most well-known of these, Webkinz and Club Penguin, offer a wider range.
Coin cell powered toys are becoming more popular and many contain rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(Unless otherwise noted, all prices are from Toys "R" Us.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, ages 3+) are plush figures the size of guinea pigs that sing a note when you press their tummy.
One press corresponds to a note, repeated presses play a song.
Several Sing-a-ma-jigs sing in harmony.
Warning: once you start squeezing, you can't stop.
For a combination of singing and dancing, Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price $60, for ages 2+) is your best bet.
Based on the Elmo Live technology developed last year, the animatronic doll offers interplay like 'Simon Says', and thanks to the innovative hinged feet with wheel locks, it masters the moon walk.
Children who tested the device use Mickey as a dance teacher. However, her parents complained about the lack of volume control.
If you're a child of the 80's, you surely remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
Now he's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, ages 3+) with a whole bunch of question cards that can turn a car ride into a lesson, with an autocorrect know-it-all teacher.
If you don't want to trust your child with your smartphone, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech's MobiGo ($60 for kids 3-8) is the cheapest and most user-friendly solution, equipped with a qwerty keyboard. However, the games it contains aren't as educational as those on the Leapster Explorer ($70, for ages 3-12), which features a new, brighter screen following Leapfrog's first major overhaul of the Leapster series.
Neither version is compatible with older cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90 for kids 3-7) uses an iTunes-like system for the games and e-books, and thanks to the SD card drive, family photos can also be viewed on it.
Finally, there's Scrabble Flash ($30 from Hasbro, for ages 8+). No larger than a matchbox, the five blocks each have their own LED screen.
The game is about matching the blocks into words before time runs out. It's great for an impromptu spelling bee.
More and more toys have some kind of online connection.
Judging by toy store offerings alone, Webkinz and Club Penguin are the most important.
For example, to gift your child an online Club Penguin animal, you can purchase a Disney Club Penguin 2" Mix 'N Match Figure Pack ($5 for ages 6-12) that includes a coin with a secret code.
If you enter the code online, your child will receive enough credits for two more parts in the Club Penguin Store.
This can be roller skates or a Puffle stuffed animal.
The newest head-cell-powered micro-robot, Hexbug Nano ($10 for ages 5 and up), is no bigger than the head of your toothbrush.
The beetle moves quickly in any direction on 12 vibrating silicone legs.
Sending him through a maze of blocks is fun.
And he can take a beating.
Ours fell off the kitchen table and even survived in our dog's mouth for a while.
Police operations in China are becoming gentler
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin strode through a city square, checking on his nervous subordinates while issuing orders with military authority and a low voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan - China's hardy guardians of urban order, feared and despised for their random crackdowns and penchant for violence - to impress viewers.
"Stand up straight!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered to them, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely past their teens, wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and pants stood to attention.
Four pairs of black pumps stood in a straight line.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held up with blue and white striped bows.
"They look average to me," Mr. Tang remarks disparagingly.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have tried to polish the image of China's city inspectors.
In one city, all new applicants must have a college degree.
Guangdong Province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced violence with stares: in 2009, 50 officers reportedly circled an improperly set up food truck and stared at the operator, who, half an hour later, packed up and left the place.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, would like to fundamentally change its image.
