Can politeness connect what divides?
Little civility erupted in Washington this week after a campaign of swear words and negativity.
Is it the omen of genuine bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before rushing back to the factional struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders failed to break the big questions to be dealt with during the so-called "lame duck session" at the end of a non-decision-making administration had.
From what is heard, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides, nor an observance of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The public meeting of the President's deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite political differences that persist among members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months breeds a mutual respect that obscures the ideological gulf that continues to separate members.
That's hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - one urging the other to show signs of cooperation and compromise while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after renewed factional warfare.
As a result, Tuesday's meeting itself, and its assessment by participants, was limited to a minimum of demands or recriminations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November elections put Washington in a mild mood, at least for a short time.
"There's no question the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"It's inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die out again.
And that's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all, whether temporarily or permanently.
A compromise on increased unemployment benefits is also on the cards, if only because Republicans can't afford to be believed to favor tax cuts for the rich while withholding support for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, optimism has grown that agreement on these issues can be reached during the lame duck session and the New START treaty can be ratified at the same time.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the 'lame duck session' may not necessarily result in lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, that short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening from now through 2012 as prelims, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the makeup of the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped educate them.
However concerned Republican leaders may be about gambling too high, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the Deficit Commission's recommendations, which include tax reform and some tax hikes, as well as raising the retirement age and cutting government spending.
Vice Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, by their own admission, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes on the commission to make their plan an official recommendation, and they're struggling to get anywhere near that number.
Most opposition is found among the elected representatives of the body, as there is little room or sympathy for compromise on financial issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will come next year in the form of partisan clashes as Republicans challenge Obama over the state budget, taxes and health care system, followed later by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
Evidence shows that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, both parties need to be careful about the public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and find compromise.
That may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there appears to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and Congressional Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans in his day.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
In that light, the courtesy on display this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take far more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still separate the two.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a haven of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of the "kleptocracy," and they pass on some of the bribes and protection money they collect to the Kremlin. The American Embassy in Russia reported in a memo in February.
Both the police and the state security service extort high protection money so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal gangs.
Each layer of the bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has dubbed the "vertical of authority" - takes its share of the money that goes up the ladder.
The memo, sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its homepage on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
Written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow's mayor, it accuses him of corruption.
He was sacked by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is little evidence that anything has been cleaned up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have consistently denied corruption allegations for years, and he has won numerous libel suits against such allegations.
In September, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt, he told a Russian television channel: "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's dirty."
> An incredible number of Russians believe their society is corrupt. Polls have shown that.
But it is unusual for individuals to be named, as was done in the ambassador's report, and it is unheard of for a diplomat from a foreign country to do so.
"Moscow's government's direct association with crime has led some to label it 'disturbed' and conclude that the government is acting more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo said.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'kryshna' (a term from the criminal/mafia world, literally meaning 'roof' or shelter) spread across the police, State Security (FSB), Service Inspectorate (MVD) and Bureau of the prosecutor as well as through the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have uncovered a three-tiered structure within Moscow's criminal world.
"Luzhkov comes first."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second tier."
"Last there are the common criminals and the criminal inspectors at the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas because the city doesn't offer any help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB is taking money from the biggest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source said it "explained that Moscow's business owners understand that it's best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime) because not only do they have more weapons, resources and power than they do criminals, but also because they are protected by the law."
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is no longer as important as it used to be."
The memo notes that while the fundraising is extensive, the shelter itself can't be very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who don't pay find their business closed very quickly - on one or two pretexts.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, while noting that he has made little progress.
The embassy memo contains descriptions of men going into the Kremlin with suitcases believed to be full of money.
"Medvedev has to rely on the bureaucrats in his fight against corruption," said Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, in a recent interview.
"But he's part of this bureaucracy."
"It's not part of the political class because a political class no longer exists in Russia."
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country is ranked 154th in a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption by the NGO Transparence International (countries are ranked from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The unveiling of the US embassy's memo, which happened late in the evening Moscow time, is sure to spark displeasure within the Russian government, although since Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's mistakes, it may also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that to solve the problems.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be fake and fumed at the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev called him Robin.
"The truth is that it is about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic politics in this country," he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't expect it to be done with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such an unethical way, you know."
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School commemorates the man who built it, later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold of northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure and where thousands of ex-soldiers still live .
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longtime supporters in Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to confront publicly those who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a school book that, for the first time, tells the story of the Khmer Rouge to children of ex-soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian tribunal convicted a former Khmer Rouge member for the first time when it sentenced former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Alnlong Veng's Khmer Rouge veterans, hampering their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is still resentment and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that studies the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It even divides families."
During Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork, or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-Ied government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border in Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla warfare from their base in the western mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok raised the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace accord led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge militants began defecting to the government, leading to the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998 led.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had not backed down, was arrested by government forces near the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the grinding poverty of rural Cambodia, and many held the movement in nostalgic memories.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their arms, the rank and file remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng
"They are rooted in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling in 1998 to make a living as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Early next year the court will try to try Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, and Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court's mandate is to try the old leaders and those primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it has not said it will prosecute beyond these four cases.
That did little to ease fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that is believed to have killed thousands of forced laborers.
One hot evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the withered grass, Im Chaem declined to discuss her Khmer Rouge past.
If the court summons her, she would refuse to go, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
"If there were no more persecutions, there would be war here."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court indicted more suspects, although experts and historians debate this.
"Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer times means gathering the broken pieces together," he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand everything."
The center created the first government-sanctioned textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It distributed the book in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's high school history book, which contains fewer than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As is often the case in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the dish," he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people will be convicted by the court."
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process complex and complicated, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are gradually gaining influence," he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
Up in the Dangrek mountains, a path overgrown with shrubs and littered with plastic waste leads to a rectangle of black soot covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was cremated on a pile of tires here after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone seller, said she didn't know much about the man who was burned here.
"But he has a strong spirit and a lot of people here go to him to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later in the day she wanted to go to Pol Pot's final resting place where she will drop a bush of ripe bananas - hoping it will bring her luck.
