The US government had been trying for years to persuade Belarus to stop collecting highly enriched uranium and appeared to have hit a hurdle last spring.
But US government officials told the Washington Post that two secret deals were struck with Belarus in the past two months to remove 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
That set the stage for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material - around £500, according to an official who remains anonymous due to the sensitivity of the issue.
The deal appears to be one of the key outcomes of Obama's April "47-nation Nuclear Security Summit," which excluded Belarus.
And it was apparently good enough to secure the former Soviet republic's invitation to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really excited by the fact that they want a seat on the Nuclear Security Summit (of 2012)."
"It proves to me that it works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Global Security Partnership, a group promoting nuclear security.
Clinton called the deal "a very significant, important step" by Belarus.
In April 2009 in Prague, Obama promised to secure all vulnerable nuclear material within four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries get rid of their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be the seventh.
A dozen countries did under the George W. Bush administration.
At the time of Obama's nuclear security summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko declared that the nation will never give up uranium.
"We keep highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilos, which is fundamentally weapons-grade, and less enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... We will not make dirty bombs out of it and we will not sell it to anyone".
"We use it for research purposes only, that's all."
Belarus, however, drew closer to the United States a few months ago when it indicated interest in reaching an agreement.
The first attempt to remove Belarus' uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was slightly contaminated, officials say.
It was loaded onto a special train that would travel more than 1,300 miles to a Russian factory for storage and disposal, officials say.
